WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
So today I'm going to be talking about covr, a package that aims to bring test coverage to the R ecosystem.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
My name is Jim Hester. I'm a software engineer at RStudio.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:21.000
I work with Hadley to write tools that make data science easier, faster, and more fun to use.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:31.000
This table is simply showing the current state of testing in the R ecosystem across various package repositories.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:38.000
So for the CRAN repository, there's about 10,000 total packages, about 2,000 of which have tests,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:46.000
which equates to around 20% of the total packages in CRAN with tests, at least some form of testing.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:51.000
In the Bioconductor repository, that proportion is a bit higher.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:02.000
About 35% of Bioconductor packages have tests, albeit with smaller number of total tests, a little over 1,000 total packages.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And ROpenSci, with a much smaller dataset, only 150 packages, but has over 50% of those packages with some testing.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:28.000
So tests are a focus of the ROpenSci organization, so it's good to see that their packages are being tested.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:37.000
So all told, around 23% of the total packages have some form of testing.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
So this plot is showing that's a similar dataset over time.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:52.000
So the x-axis is the time from January of 2000 to today.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And you can see the number of packages in the CRAN repository, so this dataset is only packages in CRAN,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
has been rising exponentially over that time and is now nearing 10,000 packages.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.000
The blue line is the packages that have at least some tests.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And the red and green line is the blue line stratified by whether the tests are using the TestStat infrastructure or some other type of testing framework.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:38.000
This plot is the same data as the previous plot, however now looking at a proportion of the total number of packages rather than absolute counts.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:52.000
The blue line is the total number of packages that are being tested, and you can see it's now over 20% in CRAN.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:08.000
The red and green line is the data in the blue line stratified by whether they're using the TestStat framework or some other type of testing framework such as RUnit or an ad hoc framework.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:18.000
You can see that in the past five years or so, the proportion of packages with tests has been dramatically increasing,

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:25.000
and this seems to be largely driven by packages using TestStat for their testing framework.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:36.000
I think this is a very encouraging plot as it shows that more and more R packages are including tests,

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:47.000
which should make for a much more robust ecosystem with fewer bugs in the future.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:59.000
So why do I think testing is useful? Firstly, for package authors to ensure that their code as it exists and as they write it is correct.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Secondly, for future contributions to packages that they do not break existing behavior and that they themselves are correct.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:25.000
So this is not only for outside contributions from other authors, but also contributions from the authors themselves,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:34.000
so from their future selves, that they don't break existing functionality when they write new functions.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And lastly, for users as sort of a badge of confidence in a given package and a way to show package quality.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:59.000
So if a package has tests and a user can be more confident that those tests are covering a large proportion of the package,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:11.000
the user can be more confident that the package has been well tested and is less likely to contain bugs that they may run into.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:20.000
So test coverage. What is test coverage? Test coverage is simply the proportion or lines of your code,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:26.000
of your package code that is actually ran or tested by your test code.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And probably more importantly, it is also the lines of code that are not tested by your package code.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:45.000
So cover is a R package I started writing in December of 2014.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:59.000
It supports local reports of your testing coverage and interactive use, as well as support for use on continuous integration servers such as Travis and also Jenkins.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:16.000
It supports R code, including S3, S4 reference class and R6 methods, which is all of the primary object oriented systems in R,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:27.000
as well as compiled code in C, C++ and Fortran in R packages. That's included in your R package.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Up until now, we've been talking only about tests, but cover also supports running on example code as well as vignette code.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:49.000
So it works not only for your actual test code, but also those other two types as well.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:55.000
So how this works for R code is fairly straightforward.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:06.000
If we define a function f with two statements and then call the trace calls function on it,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:15.000
cover transforms the body of the f function to have two counting statements.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:27.000
And these counting statements can be used to track exactly what lines or statements have been executed by that function.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:42.000
So basically what cover does is takes all of the functions in your package, replaces the bodies of the function by the modified function definition returned by trace calls,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:49.000
and then runs your test code on that modified code.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:58.000
You should notice that the counting calls do not actually modify the results of any of the code that they're tracking.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
So for a more complicated example, this is a function with a switch statement.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:21.000
You can see for each condition in the switch, each one gets its own count call.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:33.000
So we can then easily see exactly which conditions were executed by tallying up these counts.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:48.000
So for compiled code, cover uses the gcov extension that is provided in the GCC and Clang compilers.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:09:01.000
So to enable this, you need to compile your code without optimizations and with the coverage argument.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And then you run your testing code as normal.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So what that does is instruments the compiled code with coverage information,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:18.000
which is output once the process finishes,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:25.000
and then can be aggregated by the gcov binary into gcov files,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:35.000
which are then parsed by cover and included with the results from the R code in one homogeneous report.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:41.000
So I mentioned that cover can be used on Travis and continuous integration servers.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:49.000
So how that works for Travis is you can add suggests cover to your package description,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:57.000
which will automatically install cover when testing on when you're running your code on Travis.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And then in the after success block in your Travis config file,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:11.000
you add either the code cov or coveralls function call, depending on which of those two services you'd like to use.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:17.000
And then generates, you can then include a badge in your readme,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:25.000
which will make it easy for users to see exactly how much coverage your test coverage your package is using.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:47.000
So now I want to do a little demo of showing how easy it is to set up testing in your package and use cover interactively.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:11:03.000
I'm going to say new directory.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
Delete all that.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Okay, so if we just want to make a new function,

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:21.000
let's make a function add that simply adds one to a file.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Devtools is a useful package written by and maintained by Hadley Wickham,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:37.000
which contains a function use test,

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:45.000
which can be used to add a test file and all the testing framework you need for a new package.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So let's say we can write use test add, which will add our new package or a new test file.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
So we've made this function, we want to test it interactively first.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
We just say add one, add two.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.000
And this is what everyone typically does when they write a function and then test it interactively.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
So making a test is very simple.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
You use the Devtools use test to create the testing framework.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
And then you just write expectations for exactly the same thing that you just did.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:35.000
So add one, we expect to be two.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And expect equal add two, we expect to be three.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:46.000
Great. And then we can now run our tests.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:54.000
We're using Devtools test and we see there's two results, both of which succeeded.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Then if we later want to change or extend our function

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:09.000
to allow having a second parameter with how much we want to add,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
we say add one and two, it does equal three.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:20.000
So now we can add a new test with that new,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
and run our tests again.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:31.000
And we see, oh no, our first two tests are now failing

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:36.000
because our new functionality broke our existing functionality.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
We can verify that interactively.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
We just add one, oh, that equals three instead of two like we were expecting.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:50.000
The reason is our default was set incorrectly when we set up our new test.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
So now we fix that and we have a working test.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:59.000
So this is a great example of how testing can be beneficial

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:06.000
even when you are the sole developer just adding new functionality yourself.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:14.000
If we now define a new function, we'll call this add even.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:36.000
What this will do is basically add only if the second input is even.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:43.000
Otherwise, it will just return the input.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Now we can test this.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:05.000
I forgot to put my conditional here, so we'll say that's three.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
Okay, now we say it worked.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
All of our tests succeeded.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So now if we want to use cover to look at this simple package,

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:23.000
the main function you want to use is package coverage,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:30.000
which will automatically build and test your package.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
So if you just output the object that's returned,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.000
it will give you the overall coverage for your package.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
So we see here our overall coverage,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
and also break it down based on the number of files in your package.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
So the overall coverage is 75%.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
We only have one file, which is also 75%.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:56.000
If you want to look into this a little further, use the report function.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:03.000
And this first generates a simple report.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:08.000
This is actually a table, but we'll skip that for now.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:13.000
And you can look into the file and see exactly which line is missing coverage.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.000
So we only called add even with an even number.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
We never tried calling it with an odd number.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.000
So we have a missing coverage here.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:29.000
So if you wanted to fix that, call it now with an odd number.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And since it's odd, we're not going to actually add it.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:36.000
We're just going to ignore that.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
And then we can run those tests, verify they work.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.000
It does work.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.000
And then we run our coverage.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:44.000
Run the report.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And then you see now we have 100%.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.000
And we had one of these numbers at the end are the number of times

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
that each line was ran.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.000
So we see we ran this line twice to check this conditional.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:01.000
It went into this condition once and this condition once.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Some other useful functions.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:07.000
There's a as data frame method for the coverage object,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
which will output as a data frame.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:15.000
You can see the value is exactly sort of the same data that we had in our report.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
It also can aggregate by function.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
So there's an argument to the print method.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
So you print.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
So by default it groups by file, which isn't very useful in this case

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.000
because we only have one file.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
But you can also group by function.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:37.000
And this will then group the percentages by function.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
So you can see that we had two functions,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:51.000
both of which are covered 100% in this case.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:52.000
It is, I should also mention,

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.000
it is possible to run cover without a formal package.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:04.000
So if we keep our hello.r file,

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:22.000
but now make a test file that simply is running our code.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:27.000
I'll call this test demo.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:40.000
There's a file coverage function that simply takes a vector of file names

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:44.000
that define functions and that run functions.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
So we'll make our hello.r file,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.000
which is the file that's defining all of our functions.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:19:01.000
And our new test.r file that simply runs the functions.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:06.000
Then the result we get is exactly like that,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.000
which you would get from a package.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:14.000
We can see again we only ran add even with an even number,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.000
so we don't have any coverage for this odd case.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:32.000
So this is a way to use cover without a formal package.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:41.000
For a more complicated example,

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:53.000
we'll open the tidr package written by Hadley.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:20:14.000
We'll load cover.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:20.000
Again, we can use the default print method of cov on the coverage object,

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:24.000
and that will aggregate the results by file name.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:30.000
We can also group by function,

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:36.000
and this will, for every function defined in the package,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
give you the coverage of that function.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:43.000
So this is an easy way to see exactly which functions are missing coverage.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:50.000
You can also run a report on the file,

00:20:50.000 --> 00:21:00.000
which takes a little bit longer because this is a more complicated package.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:06.000
In this case, you can also sort each of these columns sortable,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
so you can sort by the number of missed lines

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:16.000
You can see there's a number of missed lines in the melt CPP file,

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
and you can see in this case,

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:23.000
here's a good candidate for additional tests.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:28.000
These other cases were checked, but this case was not.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
And since this is a little bit more complicated logic,

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:45.000
it's probably useful to check it.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:52.000
Another thing we can do is,

00:21:52.000 --> 00:22:02.000
I mentioned that cover supports not only test coverage, but also example coverage.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.000
So if you run type equals example,

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:15.000
it will run all of the code in your examples and generate coverage that way.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.000
And then if we print this, grouping by function,

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:24.000
we can see exactly which functions don't have examples.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:32.000
So the crossing function, for instance, doesn't have any examples written for it.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Again, you can do a report, same fashion.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.000
Looks exactly like it would with the tests.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:45.000
You're just running a different set of code on your package.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:56.000
We can see exactly which functions are ran by your examples.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:12.000
Similarly, you can do the same thing with your vignette.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:21.000
We'll spin the vignettes to generate a R script and then run that R script.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:33.000
We can see exactly which files or functions are included in the vignette.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:39.000
So this is a good way to see if there's portions of your package

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:54.000
that maybe you need additional long form vignettes for.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:24:03.000
One last thing I should mention is DevTools also has a use Travis function,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:07.000
which will set up Travis for your package

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:10.000
and tell you what additional steps you need to get it working.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:15.000
So if you have a package on GitHub and you would like to use Travis CI

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:19.000
for every time you push a change to the package,

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.000
which I would encourage, use Travis.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:25.000
And there's also a use coverage function

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
that you can use to set up coverage for the package.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:31.000
And it will tell you exactly the steps needed to get coverage,

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:34.000
to get the badge on your README and all of that.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:37.000
So those are two functions I'd recommend.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:51.000
So see how this looks on GitHub.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.000
You may have seen these badges.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
So this is a CodeCov badge.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:01.000
And so the way that these are actually signifying that the package is using

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:07.000
cover to generate its coverage, we can click on that.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:12.000
And it will take us to the CodeCov.io website.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:16.000
This first plot is showing the coverage over time.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:23.000
So we see coverage of this package is very steady over the last six months,

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.000
right around 92%.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:33.000
We can then drill down into exactly which files do and do not have coverage.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.000
So we see in the R files,

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
this extract numeric function doesn't have coverage.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
In this case, I think it's actually okay.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
This is now a deprecated function,

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:47.000
so we probably don't need to add additional tests.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
And that's one important thing to note,

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:53.000
is just because a package doesn't have 100% coverage

00:25:53.000 --> 00:26:02.000
doesn't necessarily mean one that does is definitely a better solution.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:08.000
Just because a package has tests that run the code

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:11.000
doesn't mean it handles all of the possible inputs.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:14.000
So there could definitely be bugs in a package,

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:20.000
even if it has 100% test coverage.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
We can see this works for compiled code as well.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:28.000
Again, we can go to our Melt C++ function,

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:31.000
or actually C function,

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and see exactly the same thing we saw interactively.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:39.000
So this is also a nice way for users

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:43.000
to sort of gauge which package they'd like to use.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.000
You see tidyr has 92% coverage.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:50.000
That's a pretty good indicator that it's a robust package

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
and likely won't have tons of...

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:55.000
you won't run into many bugs with the package.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:01.000
It's just another way, another metric someone could use.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:08.000
If you don't typically go to GitHub to look at packages,

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:14.000
one nice thing is on the package landing page on CRAN's website,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:17.000
if you click the readme,

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.000
and the package uses one of the coverage badges,

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:24.000
you can see the coverage badge directly in the readme,

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:28.000
and then click on it to take you to the CodeCov website.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:35.000
One other nice feature about CodeCov

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:39.000
is it has an extension for Chrome

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
that integrates with GitHub.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:50.000
And if a package is using the CodeCov website service

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:54.000
to track coverage,

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:57.000
it will automatically annotate the package code

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:59.000
with the coverage for you.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
So you can easily see,

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:04.000
oh, there's only 70% coverage in the utilities function,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.000
and it will also highlight the code for you.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:11.000
So I can see exactly, just when I'm browsing GitHub,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.000
exactly where I'm missing coverage.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:18.000
So this is also one of the reasons

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.000
I prefer using CodeCov on my own projects,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:25.000
is for this extension and some additional features

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:29.000
that it provides over the CoverAll service.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.000
For an example of the CoverAll service,

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.000
here's a package by Dean Attali.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:39.000
He's using CoverAll, so if we look at his...

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:44.000
repo on GitHub,

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.000
it looks very similar to how it looks with the CodeCov,

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:52.000
only the link takes you to the CoverAll service instead.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.000
And this is also very similar to the interactive report.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:01.000
So you can see all the files in the package.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:05.000
You can click on one,

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:11.000
see exactly which function doesn't have test coverage.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.000
In this case, it's the printing function.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
So that's...

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Both services are very featureful and useful,

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
and I would encourage you to use

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:31.000
whichever one you personally prefer.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:35.000
They're both fully supported by the Cover package.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:49.000
So sort of one last conclusion is,

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:53.000
are people actually using this package in our ecosystem?

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
So the Cover package.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:00.000
So this graph is showing the number of packages

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.000
and repositories, package repositories on GitHub

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:08.000
that are using Travis as well as Cover

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
with either CodeCov or the CoverAll service.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:16.000
So you can see from the first sort of release

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:19.000
of when I started writing this package to today,

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:23.000
there's well over 1,500 packages

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:29.000
between the two services that are using Cover

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:32.000
underneath to do code coverage for R.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.000
And this is an addition.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.000
I should mention the...

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
Bioconductor packages,

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:57.000
their Bioconductor organization runs Cover

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:01.000
as part of their nightly build process.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:07.000
And so we have coverage of every package

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:13.000
with testing on Bioconductor with the CodeCov service.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
And they also have these nice badges

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.000
on their package landing pages.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
So we can see the Sunrise Experiment package, for example,

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
has 70% test coverage.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:33.000
So again, this is the number of repositories on CRAN.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:37.000
So there's over 1,500 repositories,

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:41.000
GitHub packages on GitHub using this.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:44.000
Like I said, Bioconductor is running this

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.000
on all of their 1,000 packages.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:50.000
And so I think it's...

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:52.000
And then there's multiple...

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:56.000
There's, I'm sure, a number of additional package authors

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:02.000
who are not using one of the services on GitHub

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:04.000
but are using Cover interactively.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:10.000
So there's a large number of packages using this.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:14.000
And this is just the same plot broken down by service.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:17.000
So originally, I only had support for the Coverall service

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.000
in the Cover package.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
Now there's also support for CodeCov,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.000
and that seems to be a very popular option.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:29.000
And like I said, I prefer using CodeCov for my own packages.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:33.000
CodeCover is also the focus of the CodeCover's working group.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
These are the current members of the working group.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:42.000
And if anyone is interested in joining it,

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.000
you're welcome to do so.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:48.000
Primarily, the working group has been focused on

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:52.000
sort of bug fixes found in enterprise use

00:32:52.000 --> 00:33:00.000
as well as sort of using Cover more in an enterprise setting

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:09.000
such as integration with Jenkins.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:15.000
So some future work is branch coverage.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:21.000
So that's coverage sort of tallying by conditional statements

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:26.000
for each conditional if all the branches are covered.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.000
The Intel compiler, so right now there's support for GCC and Clang

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:35.000
but not for the Intel because it uses a different mechanism

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:39.000
for tracking and reporting on coverage.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:42.000
Solaris Spark system and AIX support.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:50.000
Right now we only support Windows, macOS, and Linux.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:53.000
And if you're interested in the CodeCover's working group

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
or additional features for Cover,

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:59.000
I'd encourage you to join the working group.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:04.000
There's more information at this wiki page.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:08.000
And sort of in conclusion, these are all the sort of useful functions

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:13.000
I think can be used to make your package,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:19.000
to work with coverage in your package and track coverage.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:24.000
Sort of the most important of which I think are the package coverage functions,

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:29.000
the DevTools functions to set up coverage and testing in your package,

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:35.000
the report function to generate the interactive reports.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:41.000
Some common questions I get about Cover are support for using on Jenkins.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:46.000
So there is now at least some support for doing that.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:54.000
There's a Coberta plugin on Jenkins for code coverage in Java,

00:34:54.000 --> 00:35:01.000
and we have support in Cover to generate XML files in that format.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:05.000
So you can use that to integrate with the plugin

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:12.000
and generate test coverage reports in your Jenkins instance.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:21.000
Some other common questions are using coverage and testing with Shiny apps.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:26.000
I think that's still an ongoing area of research

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:29.000
or an experimentation within RStudio.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:31.000
Shiny apps, because they are interactive,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:37.000
are a little more difficult to test than other R code.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:47.000
So once the story of testing in Shiny is more concretely understood,

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:51.000
Cover should work in a similar way.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.000
It should work just as well.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:59.000
The tricky part is getting the Shiny side of things working.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:04.000
But that's definitely something we're interested in exploring further.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:10.000
In terms of additional setup, another question that's commonly asked

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:15.000
is additional setup requirements for the compiled code.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:19.000
You basically shouldn't have to do anything additional

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.000
if your R package has compiled code.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:31.000
It should automatically work.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Automatically detect that you're using compiled code

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
and provide the necessary arguments.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:41.000
So you won't actually have to do any additional setup.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:47.000
That should just work out of the box.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:58.000
With that, I think I will thank everyone for watching this webinar.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.000
It unfortunately had to be re-recorded from the original webinar

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:07.000
because the original recording did not work.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:10.000
Thank you for bearing with us.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:12.000
If you have any issues with the Cover package,

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:19.000
I highly encourage you to open an issue on the GitHub repository.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:30.000
Simply my name, jimhester cover issues on github.com is the issue URL.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:34.000
With that, thank you for listening.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:39.000
Hope you test your package and use coverage in the future.

